    '189878368687884891206528465309407076433',
    'Placental Abruption, C-section',
    'Placental abruption',
    'What brings you to the labour ward today? I\'m thirty six weeks pregnant, and I started having really bad abdominal pain about an hour ago. It came on suddenly, and it hasn\'t gone away. I\'m also bleeding. Can you describe the bleeding? How much blood have you noticed? It\'s not a huge amount, but it\'s dark red, and it\'s been constant since it started. Have you felt the baby moving? Yes, but the movements seem different. They\'re not as strong as usual, and that\'s really worrying me. Have you had any trauma or injury recently, like a fall or a car accident? No, nothing like that. Everything was fine until this pain started. Do you have any past medical or obstetric history we should know about? This is my second pregnancy. My first was straightforward, no complications. I don\'t have any major medical conditions. Are you currently taking any medications? Just prenatal vitamins. Have you had any high blood pressure or pregnancy complications so far? My blood pressure was a bit high at my last check up, but my doctor said it wasn\'t concerning yet. Based on your symptoms, I\'m very concerned about something called placental abruption, where the placenta separates from the wall of the uterus before delivery. This can be very serious for both you and the baby. We need to act quickly. What does that mean? What\'s going to happen? First, I\'m going to examine you, and we\'ll put you on a fetal monitor to check the baby\'s heart rate. If we confirm placental abruption, you\'ll likely need an emergency cesarean section to deliver the baby safely. Is the baby in danger? The baby could be in distress if the placenta isn\'t providing enough oxygen. That\'s why we need to monitor closely and be ready to deliver if needed. Let me check you now. Your abdomen feels very firm and tender, which is consistent with placental abruption. The fetal monitor is showing some concerning heart rate decelerations. We need to prepare for an emergency C section right away. I\'m going to call the surgical team and get you to the operating room. How bad is this? It\'s serious, but we\'re going to do everything we can to make sure you and the baby are safe. The surgical team is excellent, and we\'re preparing everything now. Do you have any questions before we go to the operating room? Will I be awake during the surgery? We\'ll likely use regional anesthesia, like a spinal block, so you\'ll be awake but won\'t feel any pain. If there\'s not enough time, we may need to use general anesthesia. The anesthesiologist will discuss this with you. What about the baby? Will they be okay? The neonatal team will be in the operating room to take care of the baby immediately after delivery. They\'re prepared for any complications. Okay, I trust you. Let\'s do this. We\'re going to take excellent care of you. Let\'s get you to the operating room now. The surgery went well. We delivered a baby boy. He had some initial difficulty breathing, but the neonatal team has stabilized him, and he\'s in the neonatal intensive care unit for monitoring. His Apgar scores were five at one minute and eight at five minutes, which is a good improvement. How is he now? He\'s doing better. They\'re giving him some oxygen support, and they\'ll monitor him closely over the next few days. You\'ll be able to see him soon. And me? How am I? You lost a significant amount of blood during the surgery, but we were able to manage it without needing a transfusion. You\'ll need to stay in the hospital for a few days for monitoring, but you\'re stable now. When can I see my baby? We\'ll arrange for you to visit the NICU as soon as you\'re able to move around a bit. The neonatal team will keep you updated on his progress.',
    'Labour Ward Clinical Record\n\n\nPresenting Complaint:\n● Severe abdominal pain at 36 weeks gestation\n● Vaginal bleeding (dark red)\n\nDiagnosis:\n● Placental abruption\n\nManagement Plan:\n● Emergency caesarean section performed\n● Male infant delivered\n● Initial neonatal resuscitation required\n● NICU admission for respiratory support and monitoring\n● Maternal observation for post-operative recovery and blood loss management\n● NICU family visits arranged\n\nPatient presented to labour ward at 36 weeks gestation with sudden onset severe abdominal pain and dark red vaginal bleeding occurring approximately 1 hour prior to presentation. Patient reports decreased and altered fetal movements. No recent trauma or injury. This is patient\'s second pregnancy with uncomplicated first pregnancy. Recent antenatal history notable for borderline elevated blood pressure at last visit. Patient taking prenatal vitamins only.\n\nOn examination, abdomen firm and tender on palpation consistent with concealed haemorrhage. Fetal monitoring demonstrated heart rate decelerations indicating fetal distress. Clinical presentation consistent with placental abruption requiring immediate delivery.\n\nEmergency caesarean section performed under regional anaesthesia. Male infant delivered with Apgar scores 5 at 1 minute and 8 at 5 minutes. Neonatal team provided immediate resuscitation and respiratory support. Infant transferred to NICU for ongoing monitoring and oxygen therapy. Maternal blood loss significant but managed without transfusion requirement. Patient stable post-operatively. \n\nPost-operative plan includes continued maternal monitoring for bleeding and vital signs. Patient counselled regarding infant status and NICU care plan. Family visits to NICU arranged once patient mobilising. Both maternal and neonatal teams continuing close observation. Prognosis for both mother and infant favourable with appropriate ongoing care.',
